hoof: "To be on a tramp; to foot."

howl: "A prolonged cry of distress or anguish; a wail."
hud: "A huck or hull  as of a nut."
hued: "Having color; -- usually in composition; as  bright-hued; many-hued."
huer: "One who cries out or gives an alarm; specifically  a balker; a conder. See Balker."
huff: "A boaster; one swelled with a false opinion of his own value or importance."
hug: "A close embrace or clasping with the arms  as in affection or in wrestling."

huke: "An outer garment worn in Europe in the Middle Ages."
hulk: "To take out the entrails of; to disembowel; as  to hulk a hare."
hull: "To toss or drive on the water  like the hull of a ship without sails."
hum: "Ahem; hem; an inarticulate sound uttered in a pause of speech implying doubt and deliberation."
hump: "A fleshy protuberance on the back of an animal  as a camel or whale."
hun: "One of a warlike nomadic people of Northern Asia who  in the 5th century under Atilla invaded and conquered a great part of Europe."
hunk: "A large lump or piece; a hunch; as  a hunk of bread."
hurl: "A table on which fiber is stirred and mixed by beating with a bowspring."
hurr: "To make a rolling or burring sound."
hurt: "To wound the feelings of; to cause mental pain to; to offend in honor or self-respect; to annoy; to grieve."
husk: "To strip off the external covering or envelope of; as  to husk Indian corn."
hut: "A small house  hivel or cabin; a mean lodge or dwelling; a slightly built or temporary structure."
hyo-: "A prexif used in anatomy  and generally denoting connection with the hyoid bone or arch; as hyoglossal hyomandibular hyomental etc."
hypo: "Sodium hyposulphite  or thiosulphate a solution of which is used as a bath to wash out the unchanged silver salts in a picture."
our: "Of or pertaining to us; belonging to us; as  our country; our rights; our troops; our endeavors. See I."
ibex: "One of several species of wild goats having very large  recurved horns transversely ridged in front; -- called also steinbok."
ibis: "Any bird of the genus Ibis and several allied genera  of the family Ibidae inhabiting both the Old World and the New. Numerous species are known. They are large wading birds having a long curved beak and feed largely on reptiles."
ice: "To chill or cool  as with ice; to freeze."
iced: "Covered with something resembling ice  as sugar icing; frosted; as iced cake."
icon: "An image or representation; a portrait or pretended portrait."
icy: "Characterized by coldness  as of manner influence etc.; chilling; frigid; cold."
i'd: "A contraction from I would or I had."

idem: "The same; the same as above; -- often abbreviated id."
ides: "The fifteenth day of March  May July and October and the thirteenth day of the other months."
idle: "To spend in idleness; to waste; to consume; -- often followed by away; as  to idle away an hour a day."
idly: "In a idle manner; ineffectually; vainly; lazily; carelessly; (Obs.) foolishly."
idol: "A false notion or conception; a fallacy."
idyl: "A short poem; properly  a short pastoral poem; as the idyls of Theocritus; also any poem especially a narrative or descriptive poem written in an eleveted and highly finished style; also by extension any artless and easily flowing description either in poetry or prose of simple rustic life of pastoral scenes
il-: "A form of the prefix in-  not and in- among. See In-."
ilex: "A genus of evergreen trees and shrubs  including the common holly."
liad: "A celebrated Greek epic poem  in twenty-four books on the destruction of Ilium the ancient Troy. The Iliad is ascribed to Homer."
im-: "A form of the prefix in- not  and in- in. See In-. Im- also occurs in composition with some words not of Latin origin; as imbank imbitter."
imp: "To graft with new feathers  as a wing; to splice a broken feather. Hence Fig.: To repair; to extend; to increase; to strengthen to equip."
in-: "An inseparable prefix  or particle meaning not non- un- as inactive incapable inapt. In- regularly becomes il- before l ir- before r and im- before a labial."
inc: "A Japanese measure of length equal to about two and one twelfth yards."
inca: "The people governed by the Incas  now represented by the Quichua tribe."
inch: "Measurement an inch in any dimension  whether length breadth or thickness; -- used in composition; as a two-inch cable; a four-inch plank."
inee: "An arrow poison  made from an apocynaceous plant (Strophanthus hispidus) of the Gaboon country; -- called also onaye."
ing: "A pasture or meadow; generally one lying low  near a river."
inia: "A South American freshwater dolphin (Inia Boliviensis). It is ten or twelve feet long  and has a hairy snout."
ink: "To put ink upon; to supply with ink; to blacken  color or daub with ink."
inky: "Consisting of  or resembling ink; soiled with ink; black."
inn: "To get in; to in. See In  v. t."
into: "Indicating the passing of a thing from one form  condition or state to another; as compound substances may be resolved into others which are more simple; ice is convertible into water and water into vapor; men are more easily drawn than forced into compliance; we may reduce many distinct substances into one mass; men are led by evidence into belief of truth and are often enticed into the commission of crimes'into; she burst into tears; children are sometimes frightened into fits; all persons are liable to be seduced into error and folly."
iod-: "A prefix  or combining from indicating iodine as an ingredient; as iodoform."
ion: "One of the elements which appear at the respective poles when a body is subjected to electro-chemical decomposition. Cf. Anion  Cation."
iota: "A very small quantity or degree; a jot; a particle."
ir-: "A form of the prefix in-. See In-."
irk: "To weary; to give pain; to annoy; -- used only impersonally at present."
iron: "To furnish or arm with iron; as  to iron a wagon."
irpe: "A fantastic grimace or contortion of the body."

isle: "To cause to become an island  or like an island; to surround or encompass; to island."
ism: "A doctrine or theory; especially  a wild or visionary theory."
item: "To make a note or memorandum of."
iter: "A passage; esp.  the passage between the third and fourth ventricles in the brain; the aqueduct of Sylvius."
its: "Possessive form of the pronoun it. See It."
ivy: "A plant of the genus Hedera (H. helix)  common in Europe. Its leaves are evergreen dark smooth shining and mostly five-pointed; the flowers yellowish and small; the berries black or yellow. The stem clings to walls and trees by rootlike fibers."
ixia: "A South African bulbous plant of the Iris family  remarkable for the brilliancy of its flowers."
jack: "To move or lift  as a house by means of a jack or jacks. See 2d Jack n. 5."
jag: "To carry  as a load; as to jag hay etc."
jako: "An African parrot (Psittacus erithacus)  very commonly kept as a cage bird; -- called also gray parrot."
jam: "A preserve of fruit boiled with sugar and water; as  raspberry jam; currant jam; grape jam."
jan: "One of intermediate order between angels and men."
jane: "A kind of twilled cotton cloth. See Jean."
jar: "In deep well boring  a device resembling two long chain links for connecting a percussion drill to the rod or rope which works it so that the drill is driven down by impact and is jerked loose when jammed."
jarl: "A chief; an earl; in English history  one of the leaders in the Danish and Norse invasions."
java: "Java coffee  a kind of coffee brought from Java."
jay: "Any one of the numerous species of birds belonging to Garrulus  Cyanocitta and allied genera. They are allied to the crows but are smaller more graceful in form often handsomely colored and usually have a crest."
jeer: "A railing remark or reflection; a scoff; a taunt; a biting jest; a flout; a jibe; mockery."
jehu: "A coachman; a driver; especially  one who drives furiously."
jess: "A short strap of leather or silk secured round the leg of a hawk  to which the leash or line wrapped round the falconer's hand was attached when used. See Illust. of Falcon."

jet: "To spout; to emit in a stream or jet."

jig: "To dance a jig; to skip about."
jill: "A young woman; a sweetheart. See Gill."
jilt: "To play the jilt; to practice deception in love; to discard lovers capriciously."
job: "The hero of the book of that name in the Old Testament; the typical patient man."
jog: "A rub; a slight stop; an obstruction; hence  an irregularity in motion of from; a hitch; a break in the direction of a line or the surface of a plane."
join: "The line joining two points; the point common to two intersecting lines."
joke: "To do something for sport  or as a joke; to be merry in words or actions; to jest."
jolt: "A sudden shock or jerk; a jolting motion  as in a carriage moving over rough ground."
joss: "A Chinese household divinity; a Chinese idol."
jot: "To set down; to make a brief note of; -- usually followed by down."

juba: "A loose panicle  the axis of which falls to pieces as in certain grasses."
jube: "gallery above such a screen  from which certain parts of the service were formerly read."
jug: "To nestle or collect together in a covey; -- said of quails and partridges."
juke: "To perch on anything  as birds do."

junk: "A large vessel  without keel or prominent stem and with huge masts in one piece used by the Chinese Japanese Siamese Malays etc. in navigating their waters."
jury: "A committee for determining relative merit or awarding prizes at an exhibition or competition; as  the art jury gave him the first prize."
jute: "The coarse  strong fiber of the East Indian Corchorus olitorius and C. capsularis; also the plant itself. The fiber is much used for making mats gunny cloth cordage hangings paper etc."
kage: "A chantry chapel inclosed with lattice or screen work."
kagu: "A singular  crested grallatorial bird (Rhinochetos jubatus) native of New Caledonia. It is gray above paler beneath and the feathers of the wings and tail are handsomely barred with brown black and gray. It is allied to the sun bittern."
kail: "A broth made with kail or other vegetables; hence  any broth; also a dinner."
kain: "Poultry  etc. required by the lease to be paid in kind by a tenant to his landlord."
kaka: "A New Zealand parrot of the genus Nestor  especially the brown parrot (Nestor meridionalis)."
kama: "The Hindoo Cupid. He is represented as a beautiful youth  with a bow of sugar cane or flowers."
kami: "A title given to the celestial gods of the first mythical dynasty of Japan and extended to the demigods of the second dynasty  and then to the long line of spiritual princes still represented by the mikado."
kand: "Fluor spar; -- so called by Cornish miners."
karn: "A pile of rocks; sometimes  the solid rock. See Cairn."

kell: "The cocoon or chrysalis of an insect."
kelt: "Same as Celt  one of Celtic race."

kip: "The hide of a young or small beef creature  or leather made from it; kipskin."
kipe: "An osier basket used for catching fish."

kish: "A workman's name for the graphite which forms incidentally in iron smelting."

koel: "Any one of several species of cuckoos of the genus Eudynamys  found in India the East Indies and Australia. They deposit their eggs in the nests of other birds."

kra: "A long-tailed ape (Macacus cynomolgus) of India and Sumatra. It is reddish olive  spotted with black and has a black tail."

kyar: "Cocoanut fiber  or the cordage made from it. See Coir."

lade: "A passage for water; a ditch or drain."

laky: "Transparent; -- said of blood rendered transparent by the action of some solvent agent on the red blood corpuscles."
lalo: "The powdered leaves of the baobab tree  used by the Africans to mix in their soup as the southern negroes use powdered sassafras. Cf. Couscous."

lar: "A species of gibbon (Hylobates lar)  found in Burmah. Called also white-handed gibbon."
lark: "To catch larks; as  to go larking."
lash: "To bind with a rope  cord thong or chain so as to fasten; as to lash something to a spar; to lash a pack on a horse's back."
lass: "A youth woman; a girl; a sweetheart."

lawe: "To cut off the claws and balls of  as of a dog's fore feet."
lawn: "Ground (generally in front of or around a house) covered with grass kept closely mown."

laze: "To waste in sloth; to spend  as time in idleness; as to laze away whole days."
lea: "A meadow or sward land; a grassy field."
lead: "The action of a tooth  as a tooth of a wheel in impelling another tooth or a pallet."
leaf: "To shoot out leaves; to produce leaves; to leave; as  the trees leaf in May."

leam: "A cord or strap for leading a dog."
leap: "A passing from one note to another by an interval  especially by a long one or by one including several other and intermediate intervals."
leat: "An artificial water trench  esp. one to or from a mill."
left: "Those members of a legislative assembly (as in France) who are in the opposition; the advanced republicans and extreme radicals. They have their seats at the left-hand side of the presiding officer. See Center  and Right."

leek: "A plant of the genus Allium (A. Porrum)  having broadly linear succulent leaves rising from a loose oblong cylindrical bulb. The flavor is stronger than that of the common onion."
leer: "To entice with a leer  or leers; as to leer a man to ruin."
lend: "To let for hire or compensation; as  to lend a horse or gig."
lene: "Any one of the lene consonants  as p k or t (or Gr. / / /)."
leno: "A light open cotton fabric used for window curtains."
lens: "A piece of glass  or other transparent substance ground with two opposite regular surfaces either both curved or one curved and the other plane and commonly used either singly or combined in optical instruments for changing the direction of rays of light and thus magnifying objects or otherwise modifying vision. In practice the curved surfaces are usually spherical
leo: "A northern constellation east of Cancer  containing the bright star Regulus at the end of the handle of the Sickle."
lest: "That (without the negative particle); -- after certain expressions denoting fear or apprehension."
let: "To be let or leased; as  the farm lets for $500 a year. See note under Let v. t."
leve: "To grant; -- used esp. in exclamations or prayers followed by a dependent clause."

lewd: "Suiting  or proceeding from lustfulness; involving unlawful sexual desire; as lewd thoughts conduct or language."

liar: "A person who knowingly utters falsehood; one who lies."
lias: "The lowest of the three divisions of the Jurassic period; a name given in England and Europe to a series of marine limestones underlying the Oolite. See the Chart of Geology."
lid: "The top of an ovary which opens transversely  as in the fruit of the purslane and the tree which yields Brazil nuts."
lie: "The position or way in which anything lies; the lay  as of land or country."
lied: "A lay; a German song. It differs from the French chanson  and the Italian canzone all three being national."
lien: "A legal claim; a charge upon real or personal property for the satisfaction of some debt or duty; a right in one to control or hold and retain the property of another until some claim of the former is paid or satisfied."
lief: "Gladly; willingly; freely; -- now used only in the phrases  had as lief and would as lief; as I had or would as lief go as not."
lier: "One who lies down; one who rests or remains  as in concealment."
lieu: "Place; room; stead; -- used only in the phrase in lieu of  that is instead of."
lif: "The fiber by which the petioles of the date palm are bound together  from which various kinds of cordage are made."
life: "Something dear to one as one's existence; a darling; -- used as a term of endearment."
lift: "That portion of the vibration of a balance during which the impulse is given."
lit: "a form of the imp. & p. p. of Light."
like: "To come near; to avoid with difficulty; to escape narrowly; as  he liked to have been too late. Cf. Had like under Like a."
lilt: "A lively song or dance; a cheerful tune."
lily: "That end of a compass needle which should point to the north; -- so called as often ornamented with the figure of a lily or fleur-de-lis."
lima: "The capital city of Peru  in South America."
limb: "The graduated margin of an arc or circle  in an instrument for measuring angles."
limn: "To illumine  as books or parchments with ornamental figures letters or borders."
limp: "Lacking stiffness; flimsy; as  a limp cravat."
limu: "The Hawaiian name for seaweeds. Over sixty kinds are used as food  and have species names as Limu Lipoa Limu palawai etc."
limy: "Resembling lime; having the qualities of lime."
line: "To form into a line; to align; as  to line troops."
lint: "Linen scraped or otherwise made into a soft  downy or fleecy substance for dressing wounds and sores; also fine ravelings down fluff or loose short fibers from yarn or fabrics."
lion: "An object of interest and curiosity  especially a person who is so regarded; as he was quite a lion in London at that time."
lira: "An Italian coin equivalent in value to the French franc."
lisp: "The habit or act of lisping. See Lisp  v. i. 1."
liss: "To free  as from care or pain; to relieve."
list: "To engage in public service by enrolling one's name; to enlist."
lith: "A joint or limb; a division; a member; a part formed by growth  and articulated to or symmetrical with other parts."
lixt: "2d pers. sing. pres. of Lige  to lie to tell lies -- contracted for ligest."
loaf: "To spend in idleness; -- with away; as  to loaf time away."
loam: "To cover  smear or fill with loam."
lobe: "The projecting part of a cam wheel or of a non-circular gear wheel."
loch: "A kind of medicine to be taken by licking with the tongue; a lambative; a lincture."
lock: "To become fast  as by means of a lock or by interlacing; as the door locks close."

lode: "A metallic vein; any regular vein or course  whether metallic or not."
log: "To move to and fro; to rock."
logy: "Heavy or dull in respect to motion or thought; as  a logy horse."
loin: "That part of a human being or quadruped  which extends on either side of the spinal column between the hip bone and the false ribs. In human beings the loins are also called the reins. See Illust. of Beef."
loki: "The evil deity  the author of all calamities and mischief answering to the African of the Persians."
loke: "A private path or road; also  the wicket or hatch of a door."
loll: "To let hang from the mouth  as the tongue."
loma: "A lobe; a membranous fringe or flap."
long: "To belong; -- used with to  unto or for."
loo: "To beat in the game of loo by winning every trick."
loob: "The clay or slimes washed from tin ore in dressing."
look: "Hence; Appearance; aspect; as  the house has a gloomy look; the affair has a bad look."
lool: "A vessel used to receive the washings of ores of metals."
loom: "The state of looming; esp.  an unnatural and indistinct appearance of elevation or enlargement of anything as of land or of a ship seen by one at sea."
loon: "Any one of several aquatic  wed-footed northern birds of the genus Urinator (formerly Colymbus) noted for their expertness in diving and swimming under water. loop: "To make a loop of or in; to fasten with a loop or loops; -- often with up; as  to loop a string; to loop up a curtain."
loot: "To plunder; to carry off as plunder or a prize lawfully obtained by war."
lop: "Hanging down; as  lop ears; -- used also in compound adjectives; as lopeared; lopsided."
lope: "An easy gait  consisting of long running strides or leaps."
lord: "To play the lord; to domineer; to rule with arbitrary or despotic sway; -- sometimes with over; and sometimes with it in the manner of a transitive verb."
lorn: "Forsaken; abandoned; solitary; bereft; as  a lone lorn woman."
lory: "Any one of many species of small parrots of the family Trichoglossidae  generally having the tongue papillose at the tip and the mandibles straighter and less toothed than in common parrots. lose: "To suffer loss  disadvantage or defeat; to be worse off esp. as the result of any kind of contest."
loss: "Destruction or diminution of value  if brought about in a manner provided for in the insurance contract (as destruction by fire or wreck damage by water or smoke) or the death or injury of an insured person; also the sum paid or payable therefor; as the losses of the company this year amount to a million of dollars."
lost: "Occupied with  or under the influence of something so as to be insensible of external things; as to be lost in thought."
lour: "An Asiatic sardine (Clupea Neohowii)  valued for its oil."
lout: "To treat as a lout or fool; to neglect; to disappoint."

sao: "Any marine annelid of the genus Hyalinaecia  especially H. tubicola of Europe which inhabits a transparent movable tube resembling a quill in color and texture."
sap: "A narrow ditch or trench made from the foremost parallel toward the glacis or covert way of a besieged place by digging under cover of gabions  etc."
sard: "A variety of carnelian  of a rich reddish yellow or brownish red color. See the Note under Chalcedony."
sark: "To cover with sarking  or thin boards."
sash: "To furnish with a sash or sashes; as  to sash a door or a window."
saur: "Soil; dirt; dirty water; urine from a cowhouse."
sax: "A kind of chopping instrument for trimming the edges of roofing slates."
say: "A speech; something said; an expression of opinion; a current story; a maxim or proverb."
scab: "To become covered with a scab; as  the wound scabbed over."
scan: "To mount by steps; to go through with step by step."
scar: "A marine food fish  the scarus or parrot fish."
scot: "A portion of money assessed or paid; a tax or contribution; a mulct; a fine; a shot."
scug: "A place of shelter; the declivity of a hill."
scum: "To form a scum; to become covered with scum. Also used figuratively."
scup: "A marine sparoid food fish (Stenotomus chrysops  or S. argyrops) common on the Atlantic coast of the United States. It appears bright silvery when swimming in the daytime but shows broad blackish transverse bands at night and when dead. Called also porgee paugy porgy scuppaug."
scut: "The tail of a hare  or of a deer or other animal whose tail is short sp. when carried erect; hence sometimes the animal itself."
scye: "Arm scye  a cutter's term for the armhole or part of the armhole of the waist of a garnment."
sea: "Fig.: Anything resembling the sea in vastness; as  a sea of glory."
seah: "A Jewish dry measure containing one third of an an ephah."
seak: "Soap prepared for use in milling cloth."
seal: "To affix one's seal  or a seal."
sear: "The catch in a gunlock by which the hammer is held cocked or half cocked."
seck: "Barren; unprofitable. See Rent seck  under Rent."
sect: "Those following a particular leader or authority  or attached to a certain opinion; a company or set having a common belief or allegiance distinct from others; in religion the believers in a particular creed or upholders of a particular practice; especially in modern times a party dissenting from an established church; a denomination; in philosophy the disciples of a particular master; a school; in society and the state an order rank class or party."
see: "To be attentive; to take care; to give heed; -- generally with to; as  to see to the house."
seed: "To cover thinly with something scattered; to ornament with seedlike decorations."
seek: "To make search or inquiry: to endeavor to make discovery."
sipe: "To run or soak through fine pores and interstices; to ooze."
sipy: "Oozy; -- applied to land under cultivation that is not well drained."
seer: "A person who foresees events; a prophet."
sego: "A liliaceous plant (Calochortus Nuttallii) of Western North America  and its edible bulb; -- so called by the Ute Indians and the Mormons."
seid: "A descendant of Mohammed through his daughter Fatima and nephew Ali."
seme: "Sprinkled or sown; -- said of field  or a charge when strewed or covered with small charges."
send: "The impulse of a wave by which a vessel is carried bodily."
sept: "A clan  tribe or family proceeding from a common progenitor; -- used especially of the ancient clans in Ireland."
serf: "A servant or slave employed in husbandry  and in some countries attached to the soil and transferred with it as formerly in Russia."
set: "That dimension of the body of a type called by printers the width."
seta: "One of the spinelike feathers at the base of the bill of certain birds."
sew: "To drain  as a pond for taking the fish."
sewe: "To perform the duties of a sewer. See 3d Sewer."
sex-: "A combining form meaning six; as  sexdigitism; sexennial."
sex: "One of the groups founded on this distinction."
sext: "The sixth book of the decretals  added by Pope Boniface VIII."
shad: "Any one of several species of food fishes of the Herring family. The American species (Clupea sapidissima)  which is abundant on the Atlantic coast and ascends the larger rivers in spring to spawn is an important market fish. The European allice shad or alose (C. alosa) and the twaite shad. (C. finta) are less important species."
shag: "To make hairy or shaggy; hence  to make rough."
shah: "The title of the supreme ruler in certain Eastern countries  especially Persia."
sham: "To make false pretenses; to deceive; to feign; to impose."
shaw: "The leaves and tops of vegetables  as of potatoes turnips etc."
shed: "The passageway between the threads of the warp through which the shuttle is thrown  having a sloping top and bottom made by raising and lowering the alternate threads."
shim: "A thin piece of metal placed between two parts to make a fit."
shin: "To climb (a pole  etc.) by shinning up."
shoe: "To protect or ornament with something which serves the purpose of a shoe; to tip."
shoo: "Begone; away; -- an expression used in frightening away animals  especially fowls."
shot: "To load with shot  as a gun."
shop: "To visit shops for the purpose of purchasing goods."
show: "A pale blue flame  at the top of a candle flame indicating the presence of fire damp."
shun: "To avoid; to keep clear of; to get out of the way of; to escape from; to eschew; as  to shun rocks shoals vice."
shut: "The line or place where two pieces of metal are united by welding."
shy: "A side throw; a throw; a fling."
sida: "A genus of malvaceous plants common in the tropics. All the species are mucilaginous  and some have tough ligneous fibers which are used as a substitute for hemp and flax."
side: "To furnish with a siding; as  to side a house."
sift: "To examine critically or minutely; to scrutinize."
sigh: "Figuratively  a manifestation of grief; a lan/ent."
sign: "To write one's name  esp. as a token of assent responsibility or obligation."
silk: "That which resembles silk  as the filiform styles of the female flower of maize."
silo: "A pit or vat for packing away green fodder for winter use so as to exclude air and outside moisture. See Ensilage."
sin: "To violate human rights  law or propriety; to commit an offense; to trespass; to transgress."
sing: "To accompany  or attend on with singing."
sink: "A hole or low place in land or rock  where waters sink and are lost; -- called also sink hole."
sir: "A respectful title  used in addressing a man without being prefixed to his name; -- used especially in speaking to elders or superiors; sometimes also used in the way of emphatic formality."
sire: "To beget; to procreate; -- used of beasts  and especially of stallions."
sise: "Six; the highest number on a die; the cast of six in throwing dice."
sist: "A stay or suspension of proceedings; an order for a stay of proceedings."
site: "The posture or position of a thing."
siva: "One of the triad of Hindoo gods. He is the avenger or destroyer  and in modern worship symbolizes the reproductive power of nature."
six: "A symbol representing six units  as 6 vi. or VI."
size: "To order food or drink from the buttery; hence  to enter a score as upon the buttery book."
skag: "An additional piece fastened to the keel of a boat to prevent lateral motion. See Skeg."
skee: "A long strip of wood  curved upwards in front used on the foot for sliding."
skeg: "The after part of the keel of a vessel  to which the rudder is attached."
skid: "To check with a skid  as wagon wheels."
skin: "To produce  in recitation examination etc. the work of another for one's own or to use in such exercise cribs memeoranda etc. which are prohibited."
skip: "A passage from one sound to another by more than a degree at once."
skua: "Any jager gull; especially  the Megalestris skua; -- called also boatswain."
sky: "To throw towards the sky; as  to sky a ball at cricket."
slab: "That which is slimy or viscous; moist earth; mud; also  a puddle."
slap: "With a sudden and violent blow; hence  quickly; instantly; directly."
slat: "To set on; to incite. See 3d Slate."
slav: "One of a race of people occupying a large part of Eastern and Northern Europe  including the Russians Bulgarians Roumanians Servo-Croats Slovenes Poles Czechs Wends or Sorbs Slovaks etc."
slay: "To put to death with a weapon  or by violence; hence to kill; to put an end to; to destroy."
sled: "To convey or transport on a sled; as  to sled wood or timber."
sley: "To separate or part the threads of  and arrange them in a reed; -- a term used by weavers. See Sleave and Sleid."
slim: "Of small diameter or thickness in proportion to the height or length; slender; as  a slim person; a slim tree."
slip: "A fielder stationed on the off side and to the rear of the batsman. There are usually two of them  called respectively short slip and long slip."
slit: "A long cut; a narrow opening; as  a slit in the ear."
sloe: "A small  bitter wild European plum the fruit of the blackthorn (Prunus spinosa); also the tree itself."
slop: "Ready-made clothes; also  among seamen clothing bedding and other furnishings."
slot: "The track of a deer; hence  a track of any kind."
slub: "To draw out and twist slightly; -- said of slivers of wool."
slug: "To become reduced in diameter  or changed in shape by passing from a larger to a smaller part of the bore of the barrel; -- said of a bullet when fired from a gun pistol or other firearm."
slur: "In knitting machines  a contrivance for depressing the sinkers successively by passing over them."
snag: "To injure or destroy  as a steamboat or other vessel by a snag or projecting part of a sunken tree."
snap: "Any circumstance out of which money may be made or an advantage gained."
snip: "Small hand shears for cutting sheet metal."
snob: "A workman who accepts lower than the usual wages  or who refuses to strike when his fellows do; a rat; a knobstick."
snod: "Trimmed; smooth; neat; trim; sly; cunning; demure."
snot: "To blow  wipe or clear as the nose."
snow: "To scatter like snow; to cover with  or as with snow."
snub: "A check or rebuke; an intended slight."
snug: "To rub  as twine or rope so as to make it smooth and improve the finish."
sny: "An upward bend in a piece of timber; the sheer of a vessel."
soam: "A chain by which a leading horse draws a plow."
soc: "An exclusive privilege formerly claimed by millers of grinding all the corn used within the manor or township which the mill stands."
sock: "A warm inner sole for a shoe."
soe: "A large wooden vessel for holding water; a cowl."
sofa: "A long seat  usually with a cushioned bottom back and ends; -- much used as a comfortable piece of furniture."
soft: "Be quiet; hold; stop; not so fast."
soho: "Ho; -- a word used in calling from a distant place; a sportsman's halloo."
soil: "That which soils or pollutes; a soiled place; spot; stain."
soja: "An Asiatic leguminous herb (Glycine Soja) the seeds of which are used in preparing the sauce called soy."
soke: "One of the small territorial divisions into which Lincolnshire  England is divided."
soko: "An African anthropoid ape  supposed to be a variety of the chimpanzee."
sol: "A silver and gold coin of Peru. The silver sol is the unit of value  and is worth about 68 cents."
sola: "Alone; -- chiefly used in stage directions  and the like."
solo: "A tune  air strain or a whole piece played by a single person on an instrument or sung by a single voice."
soma: "The whole axial portion of an animal  including the head neck trunk and tail."
some: "A part; a portion; -- used pronominally  and followed sometimes by of; as some of our provisions."
son: "Jesus Christ  the Savior; -- called the Son of God and the Son of man."
sop: "To steep or dip in any liquid."
sora: "A North American rail (Porzana Carolina) common in the Eastern United States. Its back is golden brown  varied with black and white the front of the head and throat black the breast and sides of the head and neck slate-colored. Called also American rail Carolina rail Carolina crake common rail sora rail soree meadow chicken and orto."
sorn: "To obtrude one's self on another for bed and board."
sors: "A lot; also  a kind of divination by means of lots."
sort: "To suit; to fit; to be in accord; to harmonize."
sory: "Green vitriol  or some earth imregnated with it."
soss: "Anything dirty or muddy; a dirty puddle."
sou: "An old French copper coin  equivalent in value to and now displaced by the five-centime piece (/ of a franc) which is popularly called a sou."
soul: "To indue with a soul; to furnish with a soul or mind."
sour: "To become sour; to turn from sweet to sour; as  milk soon sours in hot weather; a kind temper sometimes sours in adversity."
sow: "To scatter seed for growth and the production of a crop; -- literally or figuratively."
soy: "The soja  a kind of bean. See Soja."
spa: "A spring or mineral water; -- so called from a place of this name in Belgium."
spar: "A movement of offense or defense in boxing."
spay: "The male of the red deer in his third year; a spade."
spin: "Velocity of rotation about some specified axis."
spit: "To rain or snow slightly  or with sprinkles."
spry: "Having great power of leaping or running; nimble; active."
spud: "Anything short and thick; specifically  a piece of dough boiled in fat."
spur: "To spur on one' horse; to travel with great expedition; to hasten; hence  to press forward in any pursuit."
sput: "An annular reenforce  to strengthen a place where a hole is made."
spy: "A person sent secretly into an enemy's camp  territory or fortifications to inspect his works ascertain his strength movements or designs and to communicate such intelligence to the proper officer."
stab: "Fig.: An injury inflicted covertly or suddenly; as  a stab given to character."
stag: "To watch; to dog  or keep track of."
star: "To be bright  or attract attention as a star; to shine like a star; to be brilliant or prominent; to play a part as a theatrical star."
staw: "To be fixed or set; to stay."
stay: "Strictly  a part in tension to hold the parts together or stiffen them."
stem: "To move forward against an obstacle  as a vessel against a current."
step: "A change of position effected by a motion of translation."
stet: "To cause or direct to remain after having been marked for omission; to mark with the word stet  or with a series of dots below or beside the matter; as the proof reader stetted a deled footnote."
stew: "A state of agitating excitement; a state of worry; confusion; as  to be in a stew."
stop: "Some part of the articulating organs  as the lips or the tongue and palate closed (a) so as to cut off the passage of breath or voice through the mouth and the nose (distinguished as a lip-stop or a front-stop etc. as in p t d etc.) or (b) so as to obstruct but not entirely cut off
stot: "A young bull or ox  especially one three years old."
stow: "To arrange anything compactly in; to fill  by packing closely; as to stow a box car or the hold of a ship."
stub: "To strike as the toes  against a stub stone or other fixed object."
stud: "To set with detached ornaments or prominent objects; to set thickly  as with studs."
stum: "To renew  as wine by mixing must with it and raising a new fermentation."
sty: "An inflamed swelling or boil on the edge of the eyelid."
styx: "The principal river of the lower world  which had to be crossed in passing to the regions of the dead."
sub-: "A prefix denoting that the ingredient (of a compound) signified by the term to which it is prefixed is present in only a small proportion or less than the normal amount; as subsulphide suboxide etc. Prefixed to the name of a salt it is equivalent to basic; as subacetate or basic acetate."
such: "Certain; -- representing the object as already particularized in terms which are not mentioned."
suds: "Water impregnated with soap  esp. when worked up into bubbles and froth."
sue: "To be left high and dry on the shore  as a ship."
suet: "The fat and fatty tissues of an animal  especially the harder fat about the kidneys and loins in beef and mutton which when melted and freed from the membranes forms tallow."
sufi: "One of a certain order of religious men in Persia."
suit: "To agree; to accord; to be fitted; to correspond; -- usually followed by with or to."
suji: "Indian wheat  granulated but not pulverized; a kind of semolina."
sula: "A genus of sea birds including the booby and the common gannet."
sulk: "To be silently sullen; to be morose or obstinate."
sum: "To have (the feathers) full grown; to furnish with complete  or full-grown plumage."
sun: "To expose to the sun's rays; to warm or dry in the sun; as  to sun cloth; to sun grain."
sunn: "An East Indian leguminous plant (Crotalaria juncea) and its fiber  which is also called sunn hemp."
sur-: "A prefix signifying over  above beyond upon."
sura: "One of the sections or chapters of the Koran  which are one hundred and fourteen in number."
surd: "A surd element of speech. See Surd  a. 4."
swab: "A sponge  or other suitable substance attached to a long rod or handle for cleaning the bore of a firearm."
swad: "A thin layer of refuse at the bottom of a seam."
sway: "A switch or rod used by thatchers to bind their work."
swig: "To pull upon (a tackle) by throwing the weight of the body upon the fall between the block and a cleat."
swim: "To be dizzy; to have an unsteady or reeling sensation; as  the head swims."
syn-: "A prefix meaning with  along with together at the same time. Syn- becomes sym- before p b and m and syl- before l."
tab: "A loose pendent part of a lady's garment; esp.  one of a series of pendent squares forming an edge or border."
tac: "A kind of customary payment by a tenant; -- a word used in old records."
tack: "To change the direction of a vessel by shifting the position of the helm and sails; also (as said of a vessel)  to have her direction changed through the shifting of the helm and sails. See Tack v. t. 4."
tact: "Sensitive mental touch; peculiar skill or faculty; nice perception or discernment; ready power of appreciating and doing what is required by circumstances."
tael: "A denomination of money  in China worth nearly six shillings sterling or about a dollar and forty cents; also a weight of one ounce and a third."
tag: "A child's play in which one runs after and touches another  and then runs away to avoid being touched."
tail: "To swing with the stern in a certain direction; -- said of a vessel at anchor; as  this vessel tails down stream."
tain: "Thin tin plate; also  tin foil for mirrors."
tait: "A small nocturnal and arboreal Australian marsupial (Tarsipes rostratus) about the size of a mouse. It has a long muzzle  a long tongue and very few teeth and feeds upon honey and insects. Called also noolbenger."
take: "The quantity or copy given to a compositor at one time."
talc: "A soft mineral of a soapy feel and a greenish  whitish or grayish color usually occurring in foliated masses. It is hydrous silicate of magnesia. Steatite or soapstone is a compact granular variety."
talk: "Subject of discourse; as  his achievment is the talk of the town."
tame: "To subdue; to conquer; to repress; as  to tame the pride or passions of youth."
tamp: "To drive in or down by frequent gentle strokes; as  to tamp earth so as to make a smooth place."
tang: "To make a ringing sound; to ring."
tank: "A large basin or cistern; an artificial receptacle for liquids."
tap: "To form an internal screw in (anything) by means of a tool called a tap; as  to tap a nut."
tapa: "A kind of cloth prepared by the Polynesians from the inner bark of the paper mulberry; -- sometimes called also kapa."
tape: "A tapeline; also  a metallic ribbon so marked as to serve as a tapeline; as a steel tape."
tar: "To smear with tar  or as with tar; as to tar ropes; to tar cloth."
taro: "A name for several aroid plants (Colocasia antiquorum  var. esculenta Colocasia macrorhiza etc.) and their rootstocks. They have large ovate-sagittate leaves and large fleshy rootstocks which are cooked and used for food in tropical countries."
tart: "A species of small open pie  or piece of pastry containing jelly or conserve; a sort of fruit pie."
task: "To charge; to tax; as with a fault."
tath: "To manure (land) by pasturing cattle on it  or causing them to lie upon it."
tatt: "To make (anything) by tatting; to work at tatting; as  tatted edging."
tau: "The common American toadfish; -- so called from a marking resembling the Greek letter tau (/)."
taw: "A line or mark from which the players begin a game of marbles."
taws: "A leather lash  or other instrument of punishment used by a schoolmaster."
tax: "To charge; to accuse; also  to censure; -- often followed by with rarely by of before an indirect object; as to tax a man with pride."
teak: "A tree of East Indies (Tectona grandis) which furnishes an extremely strong and durable timber highly valued for shipbuilding and other purposes; also  the timber of the tree."
teal: "Any one of several species of small fresh-water ducks of the genus Anas and the subgenera Querquedula and Nettion. The male is handsomely colored  and has a bright green or blue speculum on the wings."
team: "To convey or haul with a team; as  to team lumber."
tear: "The act of tearing  or the state of being torn; a rent; a fissure."
tore: "The solid inclosed by such a surface; -- sometimes called an anchor ring."
teat: "A small protuberance or nozzle resembling the teat of an animal."
ted: "To spread  or turn from the swath and scatter for drying as new-mowed grass; -- chiefly used in the past participle."
tee: "A short piece of pipe having a lateral outlet  used to connect a line of pipe with a pipe at a right angle with the line; -- so called because it resembles the letter T in shape."
teen: "To hedge or fence in; to inclose."
teg: "A sheep in its second year; also  a doe in its second year."
teil: "The lime tree  or linden; -- called also teil tree."
ten: "A symbol representing ten units  as 10 x or X."
tend: "To be directed  as to any end object or purpose; to aim; to have or give a leaning; to exert activity or influence; to serve as a means; to contribute; as our petitions if granted might tend to our destruction."
tent: "To lodge as a tent; to tabernacle."
ter-: "A combining form from L. ter signifying three times  thrice. See Tri- 2."
term: "To apply a term to; to name; to call; to denominate."
tern: "That which consists of  or pertains to three things or numbers together; especially a prize in a lottery resulting from the favorable combination of three numbers in the drawing; also the three numbers themselves."
tew: "A rope or chain for towing a boat; also  a cord; a string."
text: "To write in large characters  as in text hand."
that: a.  conj. & adv." "As adverb: To such a degree; so; as he was that frightened he could say nothing."
thaw: "The melting of ice  snow or other congealed matter; the resolution of ice or the like into the state of a fluid; liquefaction by heat of anything congealed by frost; also a warmth of weather sufficient to melt that which is congealed."
the: "By that; by how much; by so much; on that account; -- used before comparatives; as  the longer we continue in sin the more difficult it is to reform."
thea: "A genus of plants found in China and Japan; the tea plant."
thee: "The objective case of thou. See Thou."
them: "The objective case of they. See They."
then: "In that case; in consequence; as a consequence; therefore; for this reason."
they: "The plural of he  she or it. They is never used adjectively but always as a pronoun proper and sometimes refers to persons without an antecedent expressed."
thin: "To grow or become thin; -- used with some adverbs  as out away etc.; as geological strata thin out i. e. gradually diminish in thickness until they disappear."
this: "As an adjective  this has the same demonstrative force as the pronoun but is followed by a noun; as this book; this way to town."
thor: "The god of thunder  and son of Odin."
thou: "To use the words thou and thee in discourse after the manner of the Friends."
thud: "A dull sound without resonance  like that produced by striking with or striking against some comparatively soft substance; also the stroke or blow producing such sound; as the thrud of a cannon ball striking the earth."
thug: "One of an association of robbers and murderers in India who practiced murder by stealthy approaches  and from religious motives. They have been nearly exterminated by the British government."
thus: "To this degree or extent; so far; so; as  thus wise; thus peaceble; thus bold."
thy: "Of thee  or belonging to thee; the more common form of thine possessive case of thou; -- used always attributively and chiefly in the solemn or grave style and in poetry. Thine is used in the predicate; as the knife is thine. See Thine."
tic: "A local and habitual convulsive motion of certain muscles; especially  such a motion of some of the muscles of the face; twitching; velication; -- called also spasmodic tic."
tice: "A ball bowled to strike the ground about a bat's length in front of the wicket."
tick: "To check off by means of a tick or any small mark; to score."
tid: "Tender; soft; nice; -- now only used in tidbit."
tide: "To work into or out of a river or harbor by drifting with the tide and anchoring when it becomes adverse."
tie: "To make a tie; to make an equal score."
tier: "A row or rank  especially one of two or more rows placed one above or higher than another; as a tier of seats in a theater."
tift: "A fit of pettishness  or slight anger; a tiff."
tig: "A capacious  flat-bottomed drinking cup generally with four handles formerly used for passing around the table at convivial entertainment."
tike: "A countryman or clown; a boorish person."
tile: "Fig.: To cover  as if with tiles."
tilt: "Inclination forward; as  the tilt of a cask."
tin: "To cover with tin or tinned iron  or to overlay with tin foil."
tine: "A tooth  or spike as of a fork; a prong as of an antler."
ting: "The apartment in a Chinese temple where the idol is kept."
tint: "To give a slight coloring to; to tinge."
tip: "A hint  or secret intimation as to the chances in a horse race or the like."
tire: "To exhaust the strength of  as by toil or labor; to exhaust the patience of; to wear out (one's interest attention or the like); to weary; to fatigue; to jade."
tivy: "With great speed; -- a huntsman's word or sound."
to-: "An obsolete intensive prefix used in the formation of compound verbs; as in to-beat  to-break to-hew to-rend to-tear. See these words in the Vocabulary. See the Note on All to or All-to under All adv."
toad: "Any one of numerous species of batrachians belonging to the genus Bufo and allied genera  especially those of the family Bufonidae. Toads are generally terrestrial in their habits except during the breeding season when they seek the water. Most of the species burrow beneath the earth in the daytime and come forth to feed on insects at night. Most toads have a rough warty skin in which are glands that secrete an acrid fluid."
toco: "A toucan (Ramphastos toco) having a very large beak. See Illust. under Toucan."
tody: "Any one of several species of small insectivorous West Indian birds of the genus Todus. They are allied to the kingfishers."
toe: "To hold or carry the toes (in a certain way)."
toed: "Having the end secured by nails driven obliquely  said of a board plank or joist serving as a brace and in general of any part of a frame secured to other parts by diagonal nailing."
toft: "A place where a messuage has once stood; the site of a burnt or decayed house."
toga: "The loose outer garment worn by the ancient Romans  consisting of a single broad piece of woolen cloth of a shape approaching a semicircle. It was of undyed wool except the border of the toga praetexta."
toil: "Labor with pain and fatigue; labor that oppresses the body or mind  esp. the body."
tola: "A weight of British India. The standard tola is equal to 180 grains."
tole: "To draw  or cause to follow by displaying something pleasing or desirable; to allure by some bait."
tolt: "A writ by which a cause pending in a court baron was removed into a country court."
tolu: "A fragrant balsam said to have been first brought from Santiago de Tolu  in New Granada. See Balsam of Tolu under Balsam."
tomb: "To place in a tomb; to bury; to inter; to entomb."
tome: "As many writings as are bound in a volume  forming part of a larger work; a book; -- usually applied to a ponderous volume."
ton: "A certain weight or quantity of merchandise  with reference to transportation as freight; as six hundred weight of ship bread in casks seven hundred weight in bags eight hundred weight in bulk; ten bushels of potatoes; eight sacks or ten barrels of flour; forty cubic feet of rough or fifty cubic feet of hewn timber etc."

udal: "Allodial; -- a term used in Finland  Shetland and Orkney. See Allodial."

utia: "Any species of large West Indian rodents of the genus Capromys  or Utia. In general appearance and habits they resemble rats but they are as large as rabbits."

uva: "A small pulpy or juicy fruit containing several seeds and having a thin skin  as a grape."
uvea: "The posterior pigmented layer of the iris; -- sometimes applied to the whole iris together with the choroid coat."
uvic: "Pertaining to  or obtained from grapes; specifically designating an organic acid C7H8O3 (also called pyrotritartaric acid) obtained as a white crystalline substance by the decomposition of tartaric and pyrotartaric acids."

wynn: "A kind of timber truck  or carriage."

yam: "A large  esculent farinaceous tuber of various climbing plants of the genus Dioscorea; also the plants themselves. Mostly natives of warm climates. yunx: "A genus of birds comprising the wrynecks."
zaim: "A Turkish chief who supports a mounted militia bearing the same name."
zain: "A horse of a dark color  neither gray nor white and having no spots."

zed: "The letter Z; -- called also zee  and formerly izzard."
zein: "A nitrogenous substance of the nature of gluten  obtained from the seeds of Indian corn (Zea) as a soft yellowish amorphous substance."

zif: "The second month of the Jewish ecclesiastical year  corresponding to our May."
zimb: "A large  venomous two-winged fly native of Abyssinia. It is allied to the tsetse fly and like the latter is destructive to cattle."
zobo: "A kind of domestic cattle reared in Asia for its flesh and milk. It is supposed to be a hybrid between the zebu and the yak."
zoea: "A peculiar larval stage of certain decapod Crustacea  especially of crabs and certain Anomura."
zoic: "Of or pertaining to animals  or animal life."
zoo-: "A combining form from Gr. zwo^ n an animal as in zoogenic zoology etc."
zoon: "Any one of the perfectly developed individuals of a compound animal."
zyme: "The morbific principle of a zymotic disease."
